1. Core Rules
- Replace integer values divisible by 3 with the token "Fizz"; divisible by 5 with the token "Buzz"; divisible by both 3 and 5 (i.e., divisible by 15) with the token "FizzBuzz".
- Counting is sequential starting at a configurable start (commonly 1) and proceeding by increments of 1.
- Variations: additional divisors (e.g., 7) can map to extra tokens; rules can also be triggered by the presence of digits (e.g., any number containing the digit 5 triggers the Buzz rule).
- Common usage: generate sequence of outputs for a range [start, end] for display, testing, or interview screening exercises.

2. Algorithm Patterns
- Basic loop + conditional checks: For each integer i in range, test divisibility for all configured divisors and emit either concatenated tokens or the numeric value as string when no rule matches.
- Ordered-check pattern: to avoid incorrect outputs test composite divisibility (LCM) or aggregate tokens rather than early-returning on the first match. Do not test 3 or 5 first and return; instead collect matches for all rules and then decide.
- Streaming/generator pattern: emit results one at a time to avoid O(N) memory usage for large ranges; internal state is constant-size aside from per-item allocation.
- Table-driven pattern: store rules as list of (divisor, token) pairs and iterate the table for each number; this enables arbitrary rule sets and simpler configuration.
- Vectorized/batch pattern: for large numeric arrays, compute boolean masks per divisor and combine results to produce outputs with lower high-level loop overhead (useful in numeric libraries or dataframes).

3. Function Signatures (canonical)
- generate_fizzbuzz(n: integer, rules: List[Rule] = [(3,"Fizz"),(5,"Buzz")], start: integer = 1, concat: boolean = true) -> List[string]
  - n: number of values to produce (end = start + n - 1). Returns a project-wide list of strings sized n.
  - rules: ordered list of Rule where Rule = (divisor: integer, token: string) or Rule with additional flags.
  - concat: if true, when multiple rules match their tokens are concatenated in rule order; if false, apply priority or configured resolution.
  - Memory: O(n) output list; use streaming variant to avoid.

- fizzbuzz_stream(start: integer = 1, end: integer | None = None, rules: List[Rule], yield_numbers: boolean = true) -> Iterator[string]
  - start/end define inclusive range; if end is None, stream indefinitely until externally stopped.
  - yield_numbers: if true, when no rule matches yield the decimal representation of the number; otherwise yield an empty token or null per config.
  - Behavior: yields one element per integer in range, O(1) memory overhead.

- fizzbuzz_value(i: integer, rules: List[Rule]) -> string
  - Returns the single fizzbuzz token(s) or numeric string for integer i.

- Rule data model:
  - Rule: { divisor: integer (>0), token: string, match_on_digit: boolean (default false), priority: integer (optional) }
  - When match_on_digit=true, any number whose decimal representation contains the digit equal to divisor triggers the rule (digit rules may conflict with divisor rules; resolution controlled by concat/priority).

4. Configuration Options
- Default rules: [(3, "Fizz"), (5, "Buzz")].
- concat: boolean — when true, multiple matching rules append tokens in configured order producing e.g., "FizzBuzz" for 3 and 5; when false, a single-rule priority winner is selected.
- match_on_digit: boolean per-rule — enables digit containment triggers.
- separators: string used to join tokens beyond simple concatenation (e.g., "-" yields "Fizz-Buzz").
- output_type: one of {string, token-list, structured-object}. Structured-object example: {value: "Fizz", matched_rules: [3,5], index: 15}.
- negative_handling: {coerce_to_int, error, ignore} — how to treat non-positive ranges or negative inputs.
- zero_behavior: zero is divisible by any non-zero divisor; by default zero yields concatenated tokens for all matching rules (e.g., "FizzBuzz" for 3 & 5).

5. Performance and Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N * R) where N is number of integers processed and R is number of rules; optimize by reducing R or using mask/vector operations when R is large.
- Space complexity: O(1) extra per-item for streaming/generator; O(N) total when producing lists.
- Micro-optimizations: compute modulo once per divisor per item, avoid expensive string concatenation patterns in hot loops (use list-builder and single join at emission), and prefer integers over arbitrary-precision strings when possible.
- Scalability: for extremely large N, use streaming, chunked processing, or distributed map operations. For batch processing with numeric arrays, use vectorized operations to compute matches for each divisor then combine.

6. Edge Cases and Validation
- Non-integer inputs: explicit validation required. Options: coerce with floor/ceil/truncate, or raise type error. Document the chosen behavior.
- Divisor zero: invalid — always reject rules where divisor == 0.
- Negative divisors: either normalize using absolute value or reject; be explicit.
- Very large divisors: modulo operations are still O(1) but watch for performance with big integers in some language runtimes.
- Overflow: typical integer ranges are safe; languages with fixed-width integers may require larger types for very large N or indices.
- Localization: digit containment behavior depends on numeral system; define behavior only for ASCII decimal digits unless configured otherwise.

7. Testing and Examples (expected outputs)
- Standard sequence at positions 1..16: 1,2,Fizz,4,Buzz,Fizz,7,8,Fizz,Buzz,11,Fizz,13,14,FizzBuzz,16
- Single-value tests: fizzbuzz_value(3) => "Fizz"; fizzbuzz_value(5) => "Buzz"; fizzbuzz_value(15) => "FizzBuzz"; fizzbuzz_value(0) => "FizzBuzz" (default behavior)
- Digit-rule test: with rule (5, "Buzz", match_on_digit=true) fizzbuzz_value(52) => "Buzz" because the digit 5 is present.
- Large-range behavior: generate_fizzbuzz(n=1000000, concat=true) should stream or chunk to avoid O(N) memory allocation; expected patterns preserved.
- Boundary tests: start > end yields empty sequence (or raises, per config); negative starts handled per negative_handling option.

8. Implementation Best Practices
- Use table-driven rules to allow easy extension and unit testing.
- Prefer streaming/generator APIs in libraries to keep memory usage predictable.
- Expose structured outputs for integrations (e.g., {index, output, matched_rules}) rather than only strings.
- Provide default rule set but accept user-provided rule collections; validate rules at construction time.
- Keep core logic in a small, pure function (fizzbuzz_value) and build generators or list producers on top of it.
- Include comprehensive unit tests: rule precedence, digit rules, negative and zero handling, large inputs, and configuration permutations.

9. Troubleshooting
- Symptom: outputs produce "Fizz" instead of "FizzBuzz" for 15. Cause: early-return on first matching divisor or wrong check order. Fix: aggregate matches or check divisibility by LCM (15) first, or use concatenation model.
- Symptom: memory spike when generating large sequences. Cause: returning a list for enormous N. Fix: use streaming API or chunk output.
- Symptom: non-deterministic rule ordering in concatenation. Cause: using an unordered collection (set/dict) for rules. Fix: require an ordered list/sequence for rules and document the order guarantee.
- Symptom: incorrect handling of zero. Cause: special-casing zero or interpreting modulo incorrectly. Fix: treat zero as divisible by any non-zero divisor and document the behavior or explicitly special-case if different behavior is desired.

